            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="40"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16527082' href='vote?id=16527082&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16526461'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=whatshisface" class="hnuser">whatshisface</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16527082">5 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16527082"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="3" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16527082)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">Words are only useful insofar as they point to groups of entities that the speaker and listener agree are being pointed to. So, we should ask &quot;what is the most useful definition of life?&quot; It&#x27;s a short word, so it&#x27;s valuable real-estate. What <i>should</i> the definition of life be?<p>It&#x27;s easy to get wrapped up into discussions about words, but don&#x27;t forget that the things they point to is what&#x27;s really interesting.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16527082&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16526461%2316527082">reply</a></u>
